04827nam a22006975i 9780231511186DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20062006nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2006016022  a97802315111867 a10.7312/chun139062doi  a(DE-B1597)458754  a(OCoLC)979879899  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aDS910.2.C5bC527 2007 7aPOL0110002bisacsh04a327.51950511 aChung, Jae Ho, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBetween Ally and Partner :bKorea-China Relations and the United States /cJae Ho Chung. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2006] 4c©2006  a1 online resource (200 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Tables -- tPreface -- t1. The Rise of Korea-China Relations and the United States -- t2. A Sketch of Sino-Korean Relations -- t3. Perspectives on the Origins of the South Korea–China Rapprochement -- t4. South Korea–China Relations Before 1988 -- t5. The Political Economy of Rapprochement, 1988–1992 -- t6. The Politics of Normalization -- t7. Beyond Normalization -- t8. The Rise of China and the U.S.–South Korean Alliance Under Strain -- t9. Between Dragon and Eagle -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aChina and South Korea have come a long way since they were adversaries. The arc of their relationship since the late 1970s is an excellent model of East-West cooperation and, at the same time, highlights the growing impact of China's "rise" over its regional neighbors, including America's close allies. South Korea-China relations have rarely been studied as an independent theme. The accumulation of more than fifteen years of research, Between Ally and Partner reconstructs a comprehensive portrait of Sino-Korean rapprochement and examines the strategic dilemma that the rise of China has posed for South Korea and its alliance with the United States. Jae Ho Chung makes use of declassified government archives, internal reports, and opinion surveys and conducts personal interviews with Korean, Chinese, and American officials. He tackles three questions: Why did South Korea and China reconcile before the end of the cold war? How did rapprochement lay the groundwork for diplomatic normalization? And what will the intersection of security concerns and economic necessity with China mean for South Korea's relationship with its close ally, the United States?The implications of Sino-Korean relations go far beyond the Korean Peninsula. South Korea was caught largely unprepared, both strategically and psychologically, by China's rise, and the dilemma that South Korea now faces has crucial ramifications for many countries in Asia, where attempts to counterbalance China have been rare. Thoroughly investigated and clearly presented, this book answers critical questions concerning what kept these two countries talking and how enmity was transformed into a zeal for partnership.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / International Relations / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagez978311064977208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044247240uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/chun1390640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231511186423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780231511186.jpg  a978-3-11-044247-2  Columbia University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-064977-2  Asian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagec2000d2014  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSH